South African bourse operator, JSE, is in talks with Steinhoff to get answers on an investigation into possible accounting irregularities, JSE’s director of issuer regulation John Burke told Reuters on Wednesday. Shares in Steinhoff lost more than half their value on Wednesday after the furniture retailer said it would launch an investigation into accounting irregularities, its chief executive resigned and it postponed full-year results.  Read: Steinhoff shares plunge after CEO Markus Jooste quits Read: The funds most exposed to Steinhoff